Now I see the full stop flow:

```ts
const stopSession = useCallback(async () => {
  try {
    // Cancel the sidecar agent first so it stops consuming API tokens
    try {
      if (!isConnected()) await connect();
      await sendCommand("stopSession", { sessionId });
    } catch (cancelError) {
      console.error("[useSessionActions] Cancel query failed:", cancelError);
    }
    // Then update DB status to idle
    await stopSessionMutation.mutateAsync(sessionId);
  } catch (error) {
    console.error("Failed to stop session:", error);
  }
}, [stopSessionMutation, sessionId, agentType]);
```

The `sendCommand` call routes through the WebSocket to the query engine, which fires off a cancel request to the agent server and immediately marks the session as idle in the database while invalidating the workspace, session, and stats caches but preserving the message history. Then the mutation call handles the follow-up database update.

Once the agent server processes the cancellation, it emits both a session cancelled event and a message cancelled event back to the backend — the session event is mostly redundant since the status is already idle, but the message event triggers the actual insertion of the cancelled message and invalidates the messages cache so the UI picks up the change.

The real issue is timing: when `stopSession` runs, it immediately marks the session as idle on the frontend, which causes `isStreaming` to flip to false and the component re-renders without any indication that a cancellation happened. The cancelled message arrives later after a round trip to the agent server, so there's a window where the UI shows the session as stopped but hasn't yet received the cancelled message that would display the cancellation badge.

But if the user is saying the badge never appears at all, the problem might be in how messages are grouped into turns — the cancelled message could be getting filtered out or not associated with the right turn, so `AssistantTurn` never actually sees it. I need to check how `Chat.tsx` groups messages into turns to see if that's where the cancelled message is getting lost.

